title: The U.K.’s Gas Crisis Is a Brexit Crisis, Too
content: Until now, the government has blamed Covid-related restrictions for a spate of shortages. But as virus restrictions ease and fuel runs short, the focus is shifting to Britain’s exit from the E.U.

title: Murder Charge in Case That Renewed Outrage Over U.K. Women’s Safety
content: Sabina Nessa, 28, was killed in a park in Southeast London. A 36-year-old man has been charged with her murder.

title: ‘I Can’t Imagine a Good Future’: Young Iranians Increasingly Want Out
content: Divorce is up, fertility rates are down and many from Iran’s younger generation are postponing weddings and searching for ways to leave the country in the face of economic and political stagnation.

title: German Election Leaves Merkel’s Conservatives in Disarray
content: Sunday’s defeat has revealed a gasping conservative party. But what that means for Germany’s future is not clear as traditional left-right politics are scrambled.

title: Why the Governing Party Election Is the Main Event in Japan
content: The country has free elections, opposition parties and, lately, public discontent. So why are the Liberal Democrats nearly assured to remain in power?

title: North Korea’s Arsenal Has Grown Rapidly. Here’s What’s in It.
content: The country has one of the largest standing armies in the world, but much of its equipment is old and obsolete. North Korea has sought to make up for those shortcomings by building nuclear weapons and missiles.

title: Britain’s Gas Crisis, Explained
content: A shortage of truck drivers has led to empty fuel pumps around the country, creating long lines at gas stations and panic buying.

title: Sarah Everard Was Falsely Arrested by Her Murderer, Court Hears
content: Wayne Couzens, a British police officer who pleaded guilty to the murder of Sarah Everard, used the pretense of Covid regulations to kidnap the 33-year-old as she was walking home.

title: Tunisian President Appoints Prime Minister Amid Protests Over Power Grab
content: President Kais Saied named a political novice, Najla Bouden Romdhan, in a move that may do little to dispel fears that he is moving toward one-man rule of the nation where the Arab Spring began.

title: Canada Grants Asylum to Refugees Who Sheltered Snowden in Hong Kong
content: The move ends a long period of uncertainty for a Sri Lankan family that hosted the National Security Agency contractor in their tiny apartment in 2013.

title: Do Germany’s Election Results Signal a Left Turn for Europe?
content: It is too early to tell, but the results certainly illustrate a fragmentation in politics and the growing influence of personalities.

title: Unpopulism
content: Why are Democrats talking about scrapping some of the most popular parts of their agenda?

title: The choice for Japan’s prime minister is a party stalwart who lagged in opinion polls.
content: Fumio Kishida, a former foreign minister, prevailed in a closely fought election to lead Japan’s governing Liberal Democratic Party.

title: Your Wednesday Briefing
content: A looming ‘self-inflicted’ financial crisis.

title: W.H.O. Workers Sexually Abused Women During Ebola Mission in Congo, Inquiry Finds
content: A commission appointed by the health agency found that women and girls had been promised jobs in exchange for relationships or had been sexually exploited in order to keep jobs.

title: How the Huawei Case Raised Fears of ‘Hostage Diplomacy’ by China
content: Critics of the Justice Department deal to free the Huawei executive Meng Wanzhou say it could blunt tools like sanctions and prosecutions.

title: Your Wednesday Briefing
content: Tough questions for Gen. Milley.

title: Japan’s Most Popular Candidate for Prime Minister Is Far From a Shoo-In
content: Taro Kono has by far the highest poll numbers of any candidate to lead the governing Liberal Democrats. But party elders don’t think so highly of him.

title: 14 Cuts in 25 Minutes: How Hong Kong Censors Movies
content: The Asian film capital has cracked down on documentaries and independent productions that it fears could glamorize the pro-democracy movement.

title: A Sri Lankan shaman who touted a cure for Covid died after contracting the disease.
content: Eliyantha Lindsay White, who was not vaccinated, claimed to be able to cure coronavirus patients using a holy water.

title: Dasani’s Story
content: Eight years later, we revisit the story of Dasani, a fierce and vulnerable child of New York.

title: It’s Never Too Late to Publish a Debut Book and Score a Netflix Deal
content: Jocelyn Nicole Johnson, at 50, is not the average age of a debut author. But the public school teacher describes herself as a “literary debutante” with the October publication of “My Monticello.”

title: Your Tuesday Briefing
content: The race to form Germany’s next government.

title: Canada Doubles Its Afghan Refugee Resettlement Target to 40,000 People
content: The official announcement was made by Canada’s foreign minister on Monday evening, speaking at the United Nations General Assembly.

title: Bolsonaro’s wife was vaccinated during their visit to New York for the U.N.G.A.
content: The president of Brazil began his visit by defying a U.N. honor system requiring proof of vaccination, and four members of his entourage have tested positive.

title: North Korea Launches Short-Range Missile as Country’s Envoy Speaks at U.N.
content: The launch came just three days after the sister of North Korea’s leader, Kim Jong-un, said the country would consider holding a meeting with the South and declaring an official end to the Korean War.

title: American Siblings Barred From Leaving China for 3 Years Return to U.S.
content: Their release coincided with an agreement on Friday that cleared the way for a senior executive of Huawei Technologies, the Chinese telecommunications giant, to return to China.

title: Winner but Not Chancellor, Yet: The Race to Replace Merkel
content: Olaf Scholz, the leader of the center-left Social Democrats, narrowly won the night. But now the hard part begins — building a durable governing coalition.

title: Maps show where Merkel’s party lost ground: everywhere.
content: The conservatives who have been the dominant force in modern German politics suffered their worst defeat, while the Social Democrats and Greens made gains.

title: New Taliban Chancellor Bars Women From Kabul University
content: The new policy for Afghanistan’s premier university is another major blow to women’s rights under Taliban rule, and to a two-decade effort to build up higher education.

title: Your Tuesday Briefing
content: Germany’s election results.

title: Why Haitians in Chile Keep Heading North to the U.S.
content: Many of the Haitian migrants who recently entered Texas had taken refuge for years in Chile. Some said they faced increasing joblessness, poverty and hostility there.
